= Associating Others with Allāh Using “And” (و)

*What is Meant by This:*

It refers to linking Allāh and one of His creation using "and" in matters where the creation has some role in the outcome.


Like saying:

 • “What Allāh willed *and* you willed.” 
 
 • “I hope from Allāh *and* from you.” 
 
 • “I sought help from Allāh *and* from you.” 
 
 • “I have no one but Allāh *and* you.” 
 
 • “If it weren’t for Allāh *and* so-and-so, I would have perished.” 
 
 •  And similar expressions.
 

*Ruling:*


a) If the person believes both (Allāh and the creation) are equal in the matter,
this is Major Shirk even if he uses “ثم” (then) instead of “و” (and).


b) If the person does not believe they are equal, then this is considered Minor Shirk.


*Correct Usage of These Phrases:*


The correct way to phrase such expressions falls into two levels:



*First Level:* 

Using “ثم” (then) without believing in equality:

Example:

 • “What Allāh willed, *then* you willed.” 
 
 • “I sought help from Allāh, *then* from you.” 
 

*Second Level (Best & Preferred): *

Attributing the matter entirely to Allāh.

 Example:
 
 • “What Allāh alone willed.” 
 
 
 • “I sought help from Allāh alone.” 
 

This is the most correct and best way free of any risk of shirk (association with Allāh).



== Difference Between Using "and" vs "then"

*Using "and"*
 
Indicates equality and simultaneity, which is dangerous and could imply shirk depending on the belief.

*Using "then"*

Indicates sequence and subordination. It shows that the creation comes after and under Allāh’s will.